Filesystems, the layer that turns blocks into files.

A partition on its own is just a slice of raw bytes. To actually store files in it, you need a filesystem, a layout that records where the index of files lives, where each file's data sits, and what permissions everything carries. Without a filesystem, a partition is simply empty space.

There are several filesystems in common use on linux. The default on most distributions is e-x-t-four, which is stable, mature, well understood, and a fine general-purpose choice. The red hat family defaults to x-f-s, which is excellent for large files and heavy parallelism, but it has one important limitation: it cannot be shrunk, only grown. B-t-r-f-s, the b-tree filesystem, offers built-in snapshots, subvolumes, and raid. For removable media and the boot partition you will meet the fat family, like v-fat and e-x-fat, which are universally compatible but store no permissions and no symlinks. There is also the windows filesystem n-t-f-s, readable and writable on linux, swap, which is not really a filesystem but a special area used as virtual memory, and t-m-p-f-s, which lives in ram and vanishes on reboot. For the exam, know e-x-t-four deeply and x-f-s well; the rest are situational.

To put a filesystem onto a partition, you use the make-filesystem command, m-k-f-s, with the type as a suffix, for instance m-k-f-s dot e-x-t-four for an e-x-t-four filesystem. A few options are handy: dash capital-l sets a human-friendly label, and dash m lets you reduce the percentage of space reserved for root, which is wasteful on a large disk. But there is a stern warning that goes with all of this: making a filesystem destroys everything already on the target. There is no format-and-keep-my-data option, so always be certain you have the right device and a backup before you run it.
